the problem was solved by adding depandancy 

        &lt;dependency&gt;
            &lt;groupId&gt;org.seleniumhq.selenium&lt;/groupId&gt;
            &lt;artifactId&gt;selenium-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
            &lt;version&gt;3.14.0&lt;/version&gt;
        &lt;/dependency&gt;

To explain the answer in detail:
When we add the dependency selenium-java, it pulls under the hood among others selenium api dependency:

        org.seleniumhq.selenium:selenium-java -&gt; 3.141.59
        +--- org.seleniumhq.selenium:selenium-api:3.141.59
        +--- org.seleniumhq.selenium:selenium-chrome-driver:3.141.59  
             +--- org.seleniumhq.selenium:selenium-api:3.141.59


Now if you have any other dependency which also pulls the selenium-api as a transitive dependency(in this case I think that is selenide) then there will be a version mismatch which causes error.

By explicitly declaring the dependency as 

    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.seleniumhq.selenium&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;selenium-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;3.14.0&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

We tell our build management tool (which can also be gradle besides maven) which exact version of selenium api to pull and hence problem is solved.

